Submission protocol:
- Unless the plan is genuinely short, submit each required section separately.
- Use {{SUBMIT_PLAN_SECTION_TOOL_REFERENCE}} to stage sections one by one and validate each section as you go.
- For small-to-medium plans, prefer {{SUBMIT_PLAN_SECTIONS_TOOL_REFERENCE}} to stage every section in one batched round-trip; the batch validates ALL sections before any merge and the whole batch is rejected on the first failure.
- Use {{INSERT_PLAN_STEP_TOOL_REFERENCE}} to insert a step at a specific numbered position when you are refining an existing staged draft.
- Use {{REPLACE_PLAN_STEP_TOOL_REFERENCE}} to replace a specific numbered step when only one executor action needs revision.
- Use {{PATCH_PLAN_STEP_TOOL_REFERENCE}} to partial-update a single step (shallow-merge; missing fields are preserved). Prefer this over {{REPLACE_PLAN_STEP_TOOL_REFERENCE}} when only one or two fields change.
- Use {{REMOVE_PLAN_STEP_TOOL_REFERENCE}} to remove a specific numbered step when the staged draft contains obsolete work.
- Use {{MOVE_PLAN_STEP_TOOL_REFERENCE}} to move a step to a new position in a single round-trip (the move auto-reindexes once, so do NOT combine it with insert/remove).
- The insert/remove/move step tools automatically reindex the full steps list; do not renumber steps manually.
- Use {{VALIDATE_PLAN_DRAFT_TOOL_REFERENCE}} to run the full PlanArtifact cross-section validator without writing plan.json and without deleting the in-progress draft. Call this BEFORE {{FINALIZE_PLAN_TOOL_REFERENCE}} if you want a dry-run check.
- Use {{GET_PLAN_DRAFT_TOOL_REFERENCE}} to inspect the staged draft if you need to confirm current state after an error or resume.
- Use {{FINALIZE_PLAN_TOOL_REFERENCE}} only after every required section is staged and valid. The full cross-section validator runs at finalize_plan; on success, the staged draft is deleted.
- If the staged draft becomes unusable and you need to restart from step 1, use {{DISCARD_PLAN_DRAFT_TOOL_REFERENCE}}.
- Only use {{SUBMIT_ARTIFACT_TOOL_REFERENCE}} with artifact_type="plan" when the plan is genuinely short and can be safely submitted in one atomic payload.
- The MCP tool descriptions are the contract; the tool name and one-line description in the brokered tool list tell you what side effects to expect. Re-read the description of any tool you have not used before. Do NOT call a tool without first understanding its implicit side effects: {{REMOVE_PLAN_STEP_TOOL_REFERENCE}} fails fast on dangling depends_on and silently drops orphan AC satisfied_by_steps entries; {{FINALIZE_PLAN_TOOL_REFERENCE}} deletes the draft on success; the four step-mutation tools (insert/replace/remove/move) return an echo payload with the new step number(s), the reindex map, and the list of AC ids whose satisfied_by_steps were rewritten.

